<section xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xml:id="the-intel-isa-specification-language">
  <title>The Intel® ISA Specification Language</title>

  <para>

    The Intel<superscript>®</superscript> ISA Specification Language
    is designed for creating precise, readable, executable specifications
    of Instruction Set Architectures.

  </para>

  <section xml:id="lexical-syntax">
    <title>Lexical syntax</title>

    <section xml:id="comments">
      <title>Comments</title>

      <para>
        Two forms of comment are supported.
      </para>

        <itemizedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              Single line comments start with the characters <literal>//</literal> and continue until
              the end of the line.
            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>
              Fenced code blocks start with a line that starts with three apostrophe characters (<literal>'''</literal>)
              in the first column
              and extend until the next line that starts with three apostrophe characters (<literal>'''</literal>)
              in the first column.
            </para>

            <para>
              Fenced code blocks are not normally displayed when generating documentation.
              They are used to add additional metadata to files such as documenting the category
              of a definition or inserting documentation markup.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="numeric-literals">
      <title>Numeric literals</title>

      <para>

        Bitvector literals can be in hex or binary and can use
        underscores between digits to improve clarity. e.g.,
        <literal>0b0000_1111</literal>, <literal>0xFFFF_0000</literal>.

        The length of the bitvector is either the number of digits excluding any underscores (for binary)
        or 4 times the number of digits excluding any underscores (for hex).

        There is no syntax for writing bitvector literals in decimal. (If you
        really want to do it, the best option is to use a bitslice as in
        <literal>42[7:0]</literal>.)

        There is no syntax for writing bitvector literals whose length is not
        a multiple of 4. (If you need this, the best option is to use a bitslice
        as in the 15-bit constant <literal>0x7fff[0 +: 15]</literal>.
      </para>

      <para>

        Integer literals can be in decimal and can use underscores
        between digits to improve clarity.

        e.g., 10, 1_000_000 To write a integer literal in hex or binary, use
        the Signed and Unsigned functions.

        e.g., <literal>Unsigned(0xFFFF)</literal> or <literal>Signed(0b0111)</literal>.

      </para>

      <para status="design-note">
        <emphasis>
          Adding a function such as <literal>Bits(42, size=&gt;8)</literal> is
          not ideal because you have to use a named argument to distinguish the
          size from the value.
        </emphasis>
      </para>

      <para status="unimplemented">

        [Implementation status: hex numbers are currently
        treated as Integer. We will need to do some experiments to check
        that treating hex numbers as bitvectors reduces clutter instead
        of increasing it.]

      </para>

      <para>
        Bitmask literals consist of a prefix <literal>0b</literal>
        followed by a sequence of the following characters:
        <literal>0</literal>,
        <literal>1</literal>,
        <literal>x</literal>, and
        <literal>_</literal>.

        The <literal>x</literal> digit represents an unspecified bit.

        For example <literal>0b01xx</literal> is a 4-bit bitmask where
        bit 3 is 0, bit 2 is 1 and bits 1 and 0 are unspecified.

        You can use underscores between digits to improve clarity. e.g.,
        <literal>0b0000_xxxx</literal>.

        The length of the bitvector is the number of digits (excluding any underscores).
      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="identifiers-paths-and-keywords">
      <title>Identifiers, paths and keywords</title>

      <para>

        Identifiers are any sequence of letters, digits and underscores
        starting with a letter or underscore.

        For example, <literal>Count_Set_Bits</literal>, <literal>Unsigned</literal>, or
        <literal>length_of_block</literal>.

      </para>

      <para>

        ISA supports multiple named namespaces that act similarly to a
        simple module system.

        Paths are sequences of namespace identifiers separated by
        <literal>::</literal>.

        For example, <literal>Std::Bits::Align</literal> or <literal>FP::Add</literal>.

      </para>

      <para>

        Although not enforced by the compiler, it is recommended that all
        identifiers with global scope start with an uppercase letter and that
        all identifiers with local scope start with a lowercase letter.

      </para>

      <para status="unimplemented">

        <emphasis>

          [Implementation status: At the moment, namespace support does
          little more than let you write <literal>::</literal> in the middle of an
          identifier.

          You don’t currently need to declare a namespace and there is no check
          that you are using namespaces consistently.

          As the module system is developed, checks will be added.

          For example, when declaring an enumeration <literal>E</literal>, the
          enumeration names will be required to be in the <literal>E::</literal>
          namespace.]

        </emphasis>

      </para>

      <para>
        Keywords or reserved words are any of the following.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
and         array       as          assert      begin
bitfield    case        catch       do          downto
else        elsif       end         endcase     endfor
endif       endtry      endwhile    enumeration exception
export      for         foreign     function    if
implicit    import      let         not         of
optimize    or          others      record      repeat
return      then        throw       to          try
type        until       use         var         when
where       while       with        xor
UNSPECIFIED
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        The following are reserved for possible future use as keywords
      </para>

      <programlisting>
endmodule   ensures     file        files       impure
interface   module      ordered     pass        pure
requires    unordered
      </programlisting>

      <para status="design">

        Note that builtin types and values such as
        <literal>Bits</literal>,
        <literal>Integer</literal>,
        <literal>Bit</literal>,
        <literal>Boolean</literal>,
        <literal>True</literal>,
        <literal>False</literal>
        are not keywords because that would interfere with being able to use them in paths.

      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="lexical-operators-and-delimiters">
      <title>Operators and delimiters</title>

      <table>
        <caption>Operators</caption>

        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Symbol
            </th>
            <th>
              Meaning
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>:=</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Assignment
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>==</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Test if equal
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>!=</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Test if not equal
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>&lt;</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Test if less than
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>&lt;=</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Test if less than or equal
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>&gt;</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Test if greater than
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>&gt;=</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Test if greater than or equal
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>&gt;&gt;</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Shift right
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>&lt;&lt;</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Shift left
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>+</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Add
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>-</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Subtract
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>*</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Multiply
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>**</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Raise to the power
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>/</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Divide (both inputs must be &gt;= 0)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>%</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Remainder (both inputs must be &gt;= 0)
            </td>
          </tr>

        </tbody>
      </table>

      <table>
        <caption>Delimiters</caption>

        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Symbol
            </th>
            <th>
              Usage
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>;</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Statement separator
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>,</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Grouping (between function arguments, tuple elemets, …)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>(</literal> and <literal>)</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Grouping (around function arguments, tuples, subexpressions, …)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>{</literal> and <literal>}</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Sets
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>[</literal> and <literal>]</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Slicing/indexing of bitvectors and arrays and function definitions
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>*:</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Element access (bitslicing)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>+:</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Bitslicing
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>-:</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Bitslicing
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>:</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Type annotation
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>-&gt;</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Function return type
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>?</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Exception marker (function may throw an exception)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>!</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Exception marker (function always throws an exception)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>=</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Definitions (type synonyms, records, enumerations, exceptions, foreign functions)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>=&gt;</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Association of key/index/argument with value/behavior
            </td>
          </tr>

        </tbody>
      </table>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="ascii-charset">
      <title>ASCII character encoding</title>

      <para>
        Files should use plain-ASCII 8-bit encodings.

        We recommend that tab characters are not used because different editors display them as
        different widths.

        Note that when displaying specifications as documentation, we may use <quote>ligatures</quote> such as
        displaying the two characters <literal>&lt;=</literal> as <literal>&#x2264;</literal>
        or displaying <literal>-&gt;</literal> as <literal>&#x27f6;</literal>.
      </para>

    </section>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="types">
    <title>Types</title>

    <para>

      Types determine the set of legal values of a variable, function argument, function result, etc.

    </para>

    <section xml:id="associated-functions" status="unimplemented">
      <title>Associated Functions</title>

      <para>

        Associated functions are often defined for types.

        These are functions that apply to the named type.

        Common associated functions are:

      </para>

      <table>
        <caption>Associated functions for a function &lt;T&gt;</caption>

        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Name
            </th>
            <th>
              Meaning
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>

          <tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::To_Integer(x)
            </td>
            <td>
              Convert to integer type. (Enumerated types only.)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::From_Integer(x)
            </td>
            <td>
              Convert from integer type. (Enumerated types only.)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Next(x)
            </td>
            <td>
              Successor of <variable>x</variable> (Ordered types only)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Prev(x)
            </td>
            <td>
              Predecessor of <variable>x</variable> (Ordered types only)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Print(x)
            </td>
            <td>
              Print function for values of type <variable>T</variable>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Eq(left : &lt;T&gt;, right : &lt;T&gt;) -&gt; Boolean
            </td>
            <td>
              Equality test.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Ne(left : &lt;T&gt;, right : &lt;T&gt;) -&gt; Boolean
            </td>
            <td>
              Inequality test.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Le(left : &lt;T&gt;, right : &lt;T&gt;) -&gt; Boolean
            </td>
            <td>
              Less than or equal test. Only for ordered types.
            </td>
          <tr>

          </tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Lt(left : &lt;T&gt;, right : &lt;T&gt;) -&gt; Boolean
            </td>
            <td>
              Less than test. Only for ordered types.
            </td>
          <tr>

          </tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Gt(left : &lt;T&gt;, right : &lt;T&gt;) -&gt; Boolean
            </td>
            <td>
              Greater than test. Only for ordered types.
            </td>
          <tr>

          </tr>
            <td>
              &lt;T&gt;::Ge(left : &lt;T&gt;, right : &lt;T&gt;) -&gt; Boolean
            </td>
            <td>
              Greater than or equal test. Only for ordered types.
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

    </section>

    <programlisting>
type = type-identifier
     | type-identifier '(' expression-list ')'
     | '{' set-list '}'
     | 'array' '[' index-type ']' 'of' type
     | '(' expression-list ')'

index-type = constant-expression
           | 'type' enumeration-type-identifier

set = constant-expression
    | '..' constant-expression
    | constant-expression '..'
    | constant-expression '..' constant-expression
    </programlisting>

    <para>

      Types can refer to previously defined and builtin types;
      can be parameterized by a size parameter;
      can be sets of possible values from anothere type;
      can arrays of values of another type;
      or
      can be ordered tuples of values of multiple types.

    </para>

    <table xml:id="table.types">
      <caption>Example types</caption>

      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>
            Syntax
          </th>
          <th>
            Meaning
          </th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>

        <tr>
          <td>
            {8, 16, 32, 64}
          </td>
          <td>
            A subset of Integer containing the values 8, 16, 32, and 64.
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td>
            {0 .. 255}
          </td>
          <td>
            A subset of Integer containing all values from 0 to 255 inclusive.
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td>
            {0 ..}
          </td>
          <td>
            A subset of Integer containing all non-negative integers.
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td>
            {.. -1}
          </td>
          <td>
            A subrange of Integer containing all negative integers.
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td>
            {0..8, 16, 32, 64}
          </td>
          <td>
            A subrange of Integer containing values from 0 to 8 (inclusive), 16, 32, and
            64.
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td>
            Bits(32)
          </td>
          <td>
            A bitvector of size 32.
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td>
            array [32] of Bits(64)
          </td>
          <td>
            An array of 32 bitvectors each of size 64.
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td>
            (Boolean, Bits(32))
          </td>
          <td>
            An ordered tuple with a Boolean in the first element
            and a bitvector in the second element.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr status="unimplemented">
          <td>
            (valid : Boolean, value : Bits(32))
          </td>
          <td>
            An anonymous record with explicit fields named valid and value
            of types Boolean and Bits(32)
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <para>
      Most typechecking is performed statically but
      checking of set types is performed dynamically.

      For example, if a variable has the type <literal>{ 8, 16, 32, 64 }</literal>
      then an assignment to that variable undergoes two checks.

      First, a static check that the value being assigned has type
      <literal>Integer</literal>.

      Second, a runtime check that the value being assigned
      is a member of the set although,
      in almost all cases, the compiler is able to perform the runtime checks
      statically.

    </para>

    <para status="unimplemented">
      Note that the order of fields matters: the type
      <literal>(x : S, y : T)</literal>
      is not the same as
      <literal>(y : T, x : S)</literal>.
    </para>

    <section xml:id="builtin-types">
      <title>Builtin types</title>

      There are some builtin type identifiers.

      <table xml:id="table.builtin-types">
        <caption>Builtin types</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Name
            </th>
            <th>
              Meaning
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Std::Boolean</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Enumeration with values False and True
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Std::Integer</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Unbounded integers
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Std::Bits(n)</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Bitvectors of length n
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Std::Exception</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              Exception objects
              (see
              <link linkend="exception-definitions" endterm="exception-definitions_title"/>
              and
              <link linkend="exception-statements" endterm="exception-statements_title"/>).
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <para>

        Note that the <literal>Std::</literal> prefix is normally omitted.

      </para>

    </section>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="global-declarations">
    <title>Global declarations</title>

    <para>
      Global declarations are used to define <link linkend="type-definitions">types</link>,
      <link linkend="variable-definitions">variables</link>,
      <link linkend="function-definitions">functions</link>,
      to <link linkend="module-definition">control namespaces</link>,
      and to control compilation.
    </para>

    <para>
      The order of declarations has no impact on the meaning of a specification.

      In particular, a type, variable or function can be declared after its first use.
    </para>

    <programlisting>
declaration = type-definition
            | variable-definition
            | function-definition
            | module-definition
            | function-instantiation
            | ffi-definition
    </programlisting>

    <section xml:id="type-definitions">
      <title>Type definitions</title>

      <para>
        Type definitions allow the definition of new types such as 
        <link linkend="enumerations">enumerations</link>,
        <link linkend="records">records</link>,
        <link linkend="exception-definitions">exception objects</link>,
        <link linkend="bitfields">named fields of bitvectors</link>,
        and <link linkend="type-synonyms">synonyms for existing types</link>.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
type-definition = 'type' identifier '=' type ';'
                | 'type' identifier '(' identifier-list ')' '=' type ';'
                | 'enumeration' identifier '=' '{' identifier-list '}' ';'
                | 'record' identifier '=' '{' field-list '}' ';'
                | 'record' identifier '(' identifier-list ')' '=' '{' field-list '}' ';'
                | 'exception' identifier ';'
                | 'exception' identifier '=' '{' bitfield-list '}' ';'
                | 'bitfield' identifier '=' '{' bitfield-list '}' ';'

field = identifier ':' type

bitfield = identifier '=>' '[' slice-list ']'
      </programlisting>

        <table xml:id="table.type-definition">
          <caption>Example type definitions</caption>

          <tbody>

            <tr>
              <td>type        Size = {0 .. };</td>
              <td>Define a synonym for the type <literal>{0 .. }</literal> of non-negative integers.</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td>enumeration E = {E::A, E::B, E::C};</td>
              <td>Define three enumeration constant E::A, E::B and E::C of type E</td>
            </tr>

            <tr status="unimplemented">
              <td>unordered enumeration E = { E::A, E::B, E::C };</td>
            </tr>

            <tr status="unimplemented">
              <td>ordered enumeration P = {Q, R, S};</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td>record      Int2 = {x : Size, y : Size};</td>
              <td>Define a record with two fields</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td>record      Bits2(n : { 0 .. }) = { x : Bits(n), y : {-128 .. 127} };</td>
              <td>Define a parameterized record with two fields</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td>exception   Ex1;</td>
              <td>Define an exception constructor Ex1</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td>exception   Ex2 = { x : S, y : T };</td>
              <td>Define an exception constructor Ex2 with two fields</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td>bitfield    T = { F =&gt; [1:0], G =&gt; [2], H =&gt; [7:3] } : Bits(8);</td>
              <td>Define named slices within a bitvector</td>
            </tr>

          </tbody>

        </table>


        <section xml:id="type-synonyms">
          <title>Type synonyms</title>

          <para>
            A type synonym defines an abbreviation for a type.

            It does not define a distinct type: in a synonym <literal>type S = T;</literal>
            values of type <literal>S</literal> are valid values of type <literal>T</literal>
            and vice-versa.

            For example, we can define a synonym for the type <literal>{0 .. }</literal>
          </para>

          <programlisting>
type Size = {0 .. };
          </programlisting>

          <para>
            Type synonyms cannot be recursive: the right hand side cannot directly or
            indirectly refer to the type being defined.
          </para>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="enumerations">
          <title>Enumeration definitions</title>

          <para>
            An enumeration definition defines a new type and a list of enumeration constants.
          </para>

          <para>
            For example,
          </para>

          <programlisting>
enumeration Color = {
    Color::Red,
    Color::Green,
    Color::Blue
};
          </programlisting>

          <para>
            Note that <literal>Color</literal> plays two roles here: as the
            name of the type and as the name of the
            <link linkend="identifiers-paths-and-keywords">namespace</link>.
          </para>

          <para status="unimplemented">
            Not yet implemented: use of a prefix 'ordered' or 'unordered'
            to determine whether you can use &lt;, &lt;=, &gt;= or &gt; operators
            to compare values.
          </para>

          <para status="design">
            If we add algebraic data types, we could use the approach taken
            in Rust of having parameterized enumerations.
            For example <literal>enumeration T = { T::A(x : Integer), T::B }</literal>
          </para>

          <para status="unimplemented">
            Enumeration constants are put in the namespace associated with
            their type and, in keeping with the normal use of namespaces,
            the path must be used in the definition.
          </para>

          <section status="unimplemented">
            <para>
              The namespace also contains some automatically generated (aka
              <quote>derived</quote>) associated functions including
            </para>

            <programlisting>
pure function Color::To_Integer(x : Color) -&gt; {0..2}
pure function Color::From_Integer(x : {0..2}) -&gt; Color&quot;
pure function Color::Next(x : Color) -&gt; Color // only for ordered enumerations
pure function Color::Prev(x : Color) -&gt; Color // only for ordered enumerations
pure function Color::Eq(left : Color, right : Color) -&gt; Boolean
pure function Color::Ne(left : Color, right : Color) -&gt; Boolean
pure function Color::Le(left : Color, right : Color) -&gt; Boolean // only for ordered enumerations
pure function Color::Lt(left : Color, right : Color) -&gt; Boolean // only for ordered enumerations
pure function Color::Gt(left : Color, right : Color) -&gt; Boolean // only for ordered enumerations
pure function Color::Ge(left : Color, right : Color) -&gt; Boolean // only for ordered enumerations
            </programlisting>

            <para>
              <emphasis>[Implementation status: none of these derived
              functions are implemented yet.]</emphasis>
            </para>

            <para>
              Additional associated functions can be defined by the user.
            </para>

            <para>
              <emphasis><emphasis role="strong">Todo</emphasis>: alternative
              names for Next/Prev are Succ/Pred or
              Successor/Predecessor</emphasis>
            </para>

            <para>
              The difference between ordered and unordered enumerations is
              that values of ordered enumeration types can be compared using
              any of {==,!=,&lt;,&lt;=,&gt;=,&gt;} but unordered enumeration
              types can only be compared using {==,!=}.
            </para>

            <para>
              Implementation note: Using an ordered enumeration in a for loop is a bit
              complicated because we would ideally need one extra value in
              the type - to detect when we have incremented past the end of
              the loop.

              Two compilation schemes:

              1) A loop (<literal>for i := Red to Blue …</literal>) would use an
                  Integer <literal>c : {0..n}</literal> to count loop iterations
                  and starts the loop body with <literal>let i := E::From_Integer(c);</literal>

              2) A loop (<literal>for i := Red to Blue …</literal>) would generate
                  <literal>while i &lt;= Blue do …; if i == Blue then break; else i = E::Successor(i); end</literal>
                  to avoid incrementing i past the last value in the type.
            </para>
          </section>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="records">
          <title>Record definition</title>

          <para>
            Records consist of a number of fields and the type can be parameterized by
            a number of size arguments.

            For example,
          </para>

          <programlisting>
record Address = { segment : Segment_Identifier, offset : Bits(64) };

record Float(n : {0..}, e : {0..n-1}) = {
    is_negative : Boolean,
    exponent : {-2**(e-1) .. 2**(e-1)-1},
    fraction : Bits(n-e-1),
    is_NaN : Boolean,
};
          </programlisting>

          <section status="unimplemented">
            <para>
              Records can include constant fields whose value is calculated
              from the other fields, and default values for fields.
            </para>

            <programlisting>
record Float(n : {0..}, e : {0..n-1}) = {
    let p := n-e-1,
    sign : Boolean,
    exponent : {-2**(e-1) .. 2**(e-1)-1},
    fraction : Bits(p),
    is_NaN : Boolean := False // default value - can be omitted from initializer
};
            </programlisting>

            <para>
              <emphasis>[Implementation status: constant fields (like
              <quote>p</quote>) and default values (like
              <quote>is_NaN</quote>) are not implemented yet.]</emphasis>
            </para>

            <para>
              The associated functions automatically derived for a record
              are the constructor function (and print functions, equality
              functions, etc. The print function will be called
              <quote>Float::Print</quote>)
            </para>

            <para>
              Note that constant fields would have to be expanded out in the
              function type - which is a bit weird.
            </para>

            <programlisting>
pure function Float(
    n : {0..},
    e : {0..n-1},
    // p is omitted
    sign : Boolean,
    exponent : …,
    fraction : Bits(n-e-1), // Note that we have to expand 'p' here :-(
    is_NaN : Boolean := False
) -&gt; Float(n, e);
            </programlisting>

            <para>
              <emphasis>[Implementation status: the <quote>pure</quote>
              function property is not implemented yet.]</emphasis>
            </para>
          </section>

          <para>
            Records cannot be recursive: the type of a field cannot directly
            or indirectly refer to the record.
          </para>

        <para>
          Type parameters types must be Integer or Integer Set type.
        </para>

          <para>
            Unlike <link linkend="bitfield-definitions">bitfields</link>,
            records don't have a defined data layout.

            When storing data in a record in RAM, it is common to write
            marshalling/unmarshalling functions to explicitly convert
            the record to/from a bitvector.
          </para>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="exception-definitions">
          <title xml:id="exception-definitions_title">Exception definitions</title>

          <para>
            Exception objects consist of a number of fields.

            For example,
          </para>

          <programlisting>
exception Page_Fault = { virtual_address : Bits(64), cause : Bits(8) };
          </programlisting>

          <para>
            All exception objects have type <literal>Std::Exception</literal>.
          </para>

          <para>
            Exception objects can be created in a
            <link linkend="exception-statements">throw statement</link>.

            Different kinds of exception can be matched against in a
            <link linkend="exception-statements">try-catch statement</link>.
          </para>

          <para>
            Exceptions cannot be recursive: the type of a field cannot directly
            or indirectly refer to the exception.
          </para>

          <para status="design">
            Note that exceptions are a special case of algebraic data types.

            So we should check that the syntax will be consistent.
          </para>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="bitfield-definitions">
          <title>Bitfield definitions</title>

          <para>
            Bitfield definitions allow slices of bitvectors to be named.

            For example, given the following definition and a variable
            with type <literal>float : IEEE_FP32</literal>,
            the exponent can be extracted using
            <literal>float.exponent</literal>
            which is equivalent to <literal>float[30:23]</literal>.
          </para>

          <programlisting>
bitfield IEEE_FP32 = {
    sign =&gt; [31],
    exponent =&gt; [30:23],
    fraction =&gt; [22:0]
} : Bits(32);
          </programlisting>

          <para status="design">
            <emphasis>[Todo: At the moment, the final type must be of the
            form <quote>Bits(…)</quote>. If this was relaxed to let us
            extend an existing bitfield, we would get a limited form of
            subtyping which might be useful. This makes me wonder whether
            records could extend other records - which there may not be
            any motivation to support.]</emphasis>
            </para>

            <para status="design">
              todo: do we have bitfield constructors or update syntax?
            </para>

        </section>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="global-constants-and-variables">
      <title>Global constants and variables</title>

      <para>
        Global variables are often used to represent processor registers.
        Global constants provide symbolic names for constants such as integers,
        S-box tables, etc.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
variable-definition = 'var' identifier ':' type ';'
                    | 'let' identifier ':' type ':=' constant-expression ';'
      </programlisting>

      <para status="design">
        Question: should variables be required to have an initializer so that
        all global variables are properly initialized?
      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="functions">
      <title>Functions</title>

      <para>
        Functions are parameterized, named sequences of actions.

        Functions can return a value and can be invoked in
        <link linkend="expressions">expressions</link>.
        Functions that do not return a value (sometimes called <quote>procedures</quote>)
        can be invoked in
        <link linkend="statements">statements</link>.
      </para>

      <para>
        Functions can be defined and called using either conventional syntax
        such as <literal>F(x,y)</literal> or, to support the
        <link linkend="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_access_principle">Uniform
        Access Principle</link>,
        they can be defined and called with no
        arguments (e.g., <literal>G</literal>) or using an
        array/bitslice-like syntax <literal>H[i]</literal>.
      </para>

      <para>
        Functions can throw
        <link linkend="expressions">expressions</link>
        and both the definition and invocation of such functions must be
        marked with an exception marker.

        If a function may throw an exception, it is marked with the marker <literal>?</literal>.
        If a function always throws an exception, it is marked with the marker <literal>!</literal>.
        Functions that return a value cannot always throw an exception.

      </para>

      <programlisting>
function-definition = function-header
                      'begin'
                          statement-list
                      'end'

function-header = 'function' identifier [function-exception-marker] formal-arguments '=>' type
                | 'function' identifier [procedure-exception-marker] formal-arguments
                | 'function' identifier [procedure exception-marker] formal-arguments ':=' type

function-exception-marker = '?'
procedure-exception-marker = '?' | '!'

formal-arguments = empty
                 | '(' formal-argument-list ')'
                 | '[' formal-argument-list ']'

formal-argument = ['implicit'] identifier ':' type
                | ['implicit'] identifier ':' type ':=' expression
      </programlisting>

      <para status="implementation">
        Not yet implemented: mark functions with the keyword "pure"
        to enable the compiler to optimize function calls.
      </para>

      <section xml:id="size-arguments">
        <title>Size arguments and implicit arguments</title>

        <para>
          Arguments to a function can be used as size arguments in types
          used in the function.

          In particular, size arguments can be used in the types of other arguments
          and in the return type of the function.
        </para>

        <para>
          For example, the standard library function
          <function>Std::Bits::Zero</function>
          has the following type.

          Note that the return type depends on the size argument <variable>size</variable>.
        </para>

        <programlisting>
function Std::Bits::Zero(size : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          When an argument type depends on a size argument, the
          size argument is often redundant because its value can
          be inferred from the type of the argument.

          For example, suppose that we define a function that adds two
          bitvectors together.

        </para>

        <programlisting>
function Add_Explicit(size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), y : Bits(size)) -&gt; Bits(size)
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          We would write <literal>Add_Explicit(32, x, y)</literal> to call such a function.

          In cases like this, the size argument is redundant because the size of
          the other arguments are required to match the size argument.
        </para>

        <para>
          To avoid this redundancy and the resulting clutter, an
          argument can be marked as <literal>implicit</literal>
          when the value of the argument can be inferred from the types
          of the other arguments.

          For example, we could amend the function header as follows.
        </para>

        <programlisting>
function Add_Implicit(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), y : Bits(size)) -&gt; Bits(size)
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          Since the size argument is marked as <literal>implicit</literal>,
          the size argument is omitted when calling this  would write
          <literal>Add_Implicit(x, y)</literal>
          to call such a function.
        </para>

        <para>
          An argument can only be marked as <literal>implicit</literal> if
          it is used as a size argument in the type of another function argument.

          In particular,
          if the argument is only used in the return type,
          then it cannot be marked as <literal>implicit</literal>;
          and
          if the size calculation is a non-trivial expression such as
          <literal>Bits(size1 + 1)</literal>,
          then it cannot be marked as <literal>implicit</literal>.
        </para>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="function-variants">
        <title>Syntactic variations of function definitions</title>

        <para>
          To balance the need for precision / completeness against
          readability, functions support a number of syntactic variations.
          This is typically used for processor registers where accessing the
          register requires some calculation such as bitslicing or masking
          bits or where a register file is best understood as an array.
        </para>

        <para>
          Using this alternative syntax has no impact on the behavior of the
          functions but is used to textually simplify the appearance of the
          specification and to support the
          <link linkend="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_access_principle">Uniform
          Access Principle</link>.
        </para>

        <para>
          Where these syntactic variations are used, calls to functions must
          be consistent with the definition of the function.
        </para>

        <section xml:id="nullary-functions">
          <title>Nullary functions</title>

          <para>
            Functions with no arguments can optionally omit the parentheses.
            This is typically used for processor registers where accessing the
            register requires some calculation such as bitslicing or masking
            bits.
          </para>

          <programlisting>
function EAX -&gt; Bits(32)
begin
    return RAX[31:0];
end
          </programlisting>

          <para>
            An example of calling this function is the expression
            <literal>EAX + 4</literal>.
          </para>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="array-functions">
          <title>Array functions</title>

          <para>
            Functions with arguments can optionally use square brackets
          </para>

          <programlisting>
function XMM[r : Integer] -&gt; Bits(128)
begin
    return ZMM[r][0 +: 128];
end
          </programlisting>

          <para>
            An example of calling this function is the expression
            <literal>XMM[index]</literal>.
          </para>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="assignment-functions">
          <title>Assignment functions</title>

          <para>
            A function can be defined using assignment syntax and called using
            the normal assignment statement syntax.
          </para>

          <para>
            For example
          </para>

          <programlisting>
function EAX := value : Bits(32)
begin
    RAX := Zero_Extend(value, 64);
end
          </programlisting>

          <para>
            An example of calling this function is the statement
          </para>

          <programlisting>
EAX := Zero(32);
          </programlisting>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="array-assignment-functions">
          <title>Array assignment functions</title>

          <para>
            An example assignment function that uses the array syntax is
          </para>

          <programlisting>
function XMM[r : Integer] := value : Bits(128)
begin
    ZMM[r][0 +: 128] := value;
end
          </programlisting>

          <para>
            An example of calling this function is the statement
          </para>

          <programlisting>
XMM[index] := Zero(128);
          </programlisting>

        </section>

        <section xml:id="limited-overloading">
          <title>Function overloading</title>

          <para>
            A limited degree of function name overloading is possible:
            the same name can be used for a function and for an assignment function.

            The choice of which function is called is based on whether
            a value is being read or written and that bitslice.

            For example, the statement
            <literal>EAX := EAX + 1;</literal> increments the bottom
            doubleword of <literal>RAX</literal> by calling the function
            <literal>EAX</literal> to read the current value, adding 1, and calling
            the assignment function <literal>EAX:=</literal>.
          </para>


          <para>
            Field and array selectors can require both a read and a write.

            For example, the statement <literal>EAX[0] := 0b0;</literal>
            clears the bottom bit of EAX by calling the function <literal>EAX</literal>,
            assigning to the bitslice <literal>[0]</literal>, and calling the
            assignment function <literal>EAX:=</literal>.
          </para>

        </section>
      </section>

      <section status="draft">
        <programlisting>
function F1(x : Integer) -&gt; Integer // the most common form
function F2(x : Integer)            // no return type - can only be called from statement
function F3?(x : Integer) -&gt; Integer // function F3 may raise an exception
function F4!(x : Integer)            // function F4 always raises an exception (and therefore has no return type)
function F5(x : Integer, y : Integer := 0) -&gt; Integer // with a default argument
function F6[cpl : Bits(2)] -&gt; Integer // using alternate syntax
function F7() -&gt; Integer              // a function with 0 arguments
function F8 -&gt; Integer                // a nullary function
function F9 := value : Integer        // a nullary assignment function
function F10[cpl : Bits(2)] := value : Integer // an assignment function
function F11(implicit n : {0..}, x : Bits(n)) -&gt; Bits(2*n)
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          Note that the way a function is declared must match how it is
          called.
        </para>

        <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
          <listitem>
            <para>
              If declared using (), it must be called using ()
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              If declared using [], it must be called using []
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              If declared as a nullary function, it must be called as a
              nullary function
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              If declared as an assignment function, it must be used in an
              assignment
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              If declared with a return type, it must be used in an
              expression
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              If declared with no return type, it must be used in a
              statement
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              If declared using an exception marker, it must be called
              with the same exception marker
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              If declared using an implicit argument, the argument must be
              omitted when calling a function using positional arguments
              but the argument may be provided when calling a function
              using named arguments.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist>

        <para>
          todo: The way a function is declared also affects the function
          itself. todo: rules about return statements, raising exceptions,
          exception markers, etc.
        </para>

        <para>
          todo: Should we require that all implicit arguments are provided
          last in a function declaration - to keep the story about mixing
          positional and named arguments simple?
        </para>

      </section>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="function-instantiation">
      <title>Function instantiation</title>

        <para>
          When generating code in almost any programming language, we have
          to create specialized versions of functions where each version
          is specialized to the bitwidths used in the type of the
          function. However, sometimes we need to specialize functions to
          values that are not obviously bitwidths. This can be done by
          explicitly requesting that certain sizes are optimized.
        </para>

        <programlisting>
function-instantiation = 'optimize' 'function' function-identifier 'with' '{' argument-value-list '}' ';'

argument-value = identifier '=>' constant-expression
                | identifier '=>' '_'
        </programlisting>

        <programlisting>
optimize function F with {size =&gt; 8};
optimize function F with {size =&gt; 16};
optimize function F with {size =&gt; 32};
optimize function F with {size =&gt; 64};
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          This requests the compiler to generate a specialized version
          of <function>F</function> for each specified constant <variable>c</variable>
          and to replace calls to <function>F</function> where
          argument size is equal to <variable>c</variable> with a call to the specialized
          function.
        </para>

        <para>
          We also support this useful shorthand
          to create a specialized version of a function for any concrete
          value of <variable>size</variable> used in the specification.

        </para>

        <programlisting>
optimize function F with {size =&gt; _};
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          That is, if some function G <emphasis>or</emphasis> a specialized
          version of G contains a call to F where the argument size is a constant
          c, then a specialized version of F is created as if the user had
          written <literal>function F with {size =&gt; c};</literal>.

        </para>

        <para>
          Function instantiation changes (or, rather, makes possible) the compilation of
          a specification but does not change the meaning of a specification
          so we recommend that the <literal>optimize</literal> clauses are
          kept separate from the main specification: in a separate file or
          directory.
        </para>

        <para>
          Note that this feature is backend-specific, it has no semantic
          meaning and is only needed with some code generation strategies.
        </para>

        <para status="design">
          The implementation has to specialize parameterized types to
          support this so adding explicit syntax to specialize types
          and provide a name of the users choice would be useful.
        </para>

        <para status="implementation">
          At the moment, it is only possible to use Integer constants
          when specializing a function.
        </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="foreign-import-and-export">
      <title>Foreign import and export</title>

      <para>
        Foreign import/export declarations are used to define the
        interface between C/C++ and the specification.
      </para>

      <para>
        Foreign import is used to allow the specification to use a
        function, variable or type that is defined in C/C++.

        Foreign export is used to allow C/C++ code to access a
        function, variable or type that is defined in the specification.
      </para>

      <para>
        Foreign import/export clauses provide a C/C++ identifier enclosed
        in double-quotes and support
        <link linkend="function-instantiation">function instantiation</link>.
      </para>


      <programlisting>
ffi-definition = 'foreign' ('import' | 'export') 'function' string-literal '=' function-identifier 'with' '{' argument-value-list '}' ';'
               | 'foreign' ('import' | 'export') 'var' string-literal '=' variable-identifier ';'
               | 'foreign' ('import' | 'export') 'type' string-literal '=' type-identifier ';'

argument-value = identifier '=>' constant-expression
               | identifier '=>' '_'
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        Note that this feature is backend-specific: it may change if
        generating code in a different language.
      </para>

      <para status="draft">
        todo: describe the restrictions on types that can be exported and rules about
        how types are mapped to C types.
      </para>

      <table>
        <caption>Foreign type mapping</caption>

        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Specification type
            </th>
            <th>
              C type
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Boolean</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              <literal>bool</literal>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Bits(size)</literal> where size in {1..8}
            </td>
            <td>
              <literal>uint8_t</literal>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Bits(size)</literal> where size in {9..16}
            </td>
            <td>
              <literal>uint16_t</literal>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Bits(size)</literal> where size in {17..32}
            </td>
            <td>
              <literal>uint32_t</literal>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Bits(size)</literal> where size in {33..64}
            </td>
            <td>
              <literal>uint64_t</literal>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Bits(size)</literal> where size > 64
            </td>
            <td>
              <literal>uint64_t[ceiling(size / 64)]</literal>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>Integer</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              <literal>int64_t</literal> (note that this may not be big enough to hold all Integers)
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              <literal>String</literal>
            </td>
            <td>
              <literal>const char*</literal>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              Any enumerated type
            </td>
            <td>
              The type is exported directly.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              Records
            </td>
            <td>
              Not supported at present.
            </td>
          </tr>

        </tbody>
      </table>


      <section xml:id="foreign-functions">
        <title>Foreign Functions</title>

        <para>
          For example, to allow C code to call
          a function F optimized with a size parameter using the C name <literal>F_32</literal>;
          a function G using the C name <literal>G</literal>;
          and to allow the specification to call a pair of C functions
          <literal>H_32</literal>
          and <literal>H_64</literal>
          using the name <literal>H</literal>, use
          the following foreign import/export clauses.
        </para>

        <programlisting>
foreign export function &quot;F_32&quot; = F with {size =&gt; 32};
foreign export function &quot;G&quot; = G with {};
foreign import function &quot;H_32&quot; = G with {size =&gt; 32};
foreign import function &quot;H_64&quot; = G with {size =&gt; 64};
        </programlisting>

        <para status="implementation">
          Not yet implemented: mark functions with the keyword "pure"
          to enable the compiler to optimize foreign function calls.
        </para>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="foreign-variables">
        <title>Foreign Variables</title>

        <para>
          To enable C/C++ code to read/write a variable in the
          specification, use a <quote>foreign export</quote>
          declaration; and to enable the specification to read/write a
          C/C++ variable, use a <quote>foreign import</quote>
          declaration.
        </para>

        <programlisting>
foreign export var &quot;Spec_X&quot; = X;
foreign import var &quot;Config_Y&quot; = Y;
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          In both cases, the variable is accessed by calling functions
          to convert between the C/C++ type and the .isa type.
        </para>

        <para>
          In a <quote>foreign export</quote>, a pair of C/C++ functions
          are generated with name <quote>{nm}Read</quote> and
          <quote>{nm}Write</quote> (where <quote>{nm}</quote> is the
          name in quotes).
        </para>

        <para>
          In a <quote>foreign import</quote>, a pair of nullary .isa
          function are generated: a nullary function to read the
          variable and a nullary assignment function to write the
          variable. The name in quotes is the name of the variable.
        </para>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="foreign-types" status="unimplemented">
        <title>Foreign Types</title>

        <para>
          To enable C/C++ code to interface with functions and variables
          that have user-defined types, use a <quote>foreign
          export</quote> declaration. This generates the conversion
          functions required.
        </para>

        <programlisting>
foreign export type &quot;Address_t&quot; = Bits(64);
        </programlisting>

        <para status="design">
          Todo: A slight modification of this design would use a a
          <quote>foreign export type</quote> declaration to provide the
          code needed to convert a .isa value to C/C++ and a
          <quote>foreign import type</quote> declaration to provide the
          code needed to convert a C/C++ value to .isa. This part of the
          language should be considered unstable.
        </para>

      </section>

    </section>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="expressions">
    <title>Expressions</title>

    <para>
      Expressions are used to calculate values.

      Expressions can fail due to problems such as division by zero or out-of-bound
      array indices.

      Expressions can have side-effects such as modifying a global variable and can throw an exception
      if they call a function with side-effects or that throws an exception.
    </para>

      <programlisting>
expression = atomic-expression
           | unary-operator expression
           | expression binary-operator expression
           | if-expression
           | slice-expression
           | aggregate-expression
           | function-call
      </programlisting>

    <section xml:id="atomic-expressions">
      <title>Atomic expressions</title>

      <programlisting>
atomic-expression = integer-literal
           | bitvector-literal
           | string-literal
           | variable-identifier
           | constant-identifier
           | 'UNSPECIFIED' : type
           | '(' expression ')'
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        Atomic expressions consist of
        numeric literals (integers and bitvectors),
        names of enumeration constants,
        variables, and <literal>UNSPECIFIED</literal> values.
      </para>

      <para>
        If an identifier was declared as a constant or an enumeration constant,
        then use of that identifier in an expression indicates the value of that constant.
      </para>

      <para>
        If an identifier was declared as a variable,
        then use of that identifier indicates a read of the current value of the variable.
      </para>

      <para>
        An unspecified value of type <literal>T</literal> is written <literal>UNSPECIFIED : T</literal>.
        An implementation is free to choose any value of type <literal>T</literal> each time
        that an unspecified expression is executed.

        There is no expectation that the value will be consistent, random/fair, or different each
        time an expression is executed.
      </para>

      <para>
        Note that a concrete value is chosen each time the expression is executed.

        This means that the following assertion never fails.

        <programlisting>
let x := UNSPECIFIED : Bits(8);
assert x == x; // This assertion never fails
        </programlisting>

        the following assertion will always fail

        <programlisting>
let x := UNSPECIFIED : Bits(8);
assert x != x; // This assertion always fails
        </programlisting>

        and evaluating UNSPECIFIED twice could cause the following assertion to fail (but does not guarantee it)

        <programlisting>
assert (UNSPECIFIED : Bits(8)) == (UNSPECIFIED : Bits(8)); // This assertion could fail
        </programlisting>

      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="arithmetic-operators">
      <title>Arithmetic operators</title>

      <table>
        <caption>Arithmetic operators</caption>

        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Operator
            </th>
            <th>
              Types supported
            </th>
            <th>
              Meaning
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x + y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer, Bits
            </td>
            <td>
              Addition
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x - y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer, Bits
            </td>
            <td>
              Subtraction
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x * y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer, Bits
            </td>
            <td>
              Multiplication
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x / y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer
            </td>
            <td>
              Division for positive inputs. Requires x &gt;=0, y &gt;
              0
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x % y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer
            </td>
            <td>
              Remainder for positive inputs. Require x &gt;= 0, y &gt;
              0
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              -x
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer
            </td>
            <td>
              Negation
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x ** y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer
            </td>
            <td>
              Exponentiation
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x &lt;&lt; y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer
            </td>
            <td>
              Shift left == x * 2**y. Requires y &gt;= 0
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x &gt;&gt; y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer
            </td>
            <td>
              Shift right == x / 2**y. Requires y &gt;= 0
            </td>
          </tr>

        </tbody>
      </table>

      <para>
        Note that the division operators <literal>/</literal> and <literal>%</literal>
        produce a runtime error on negative inputs (and for division by zero).

        This avoids confusion about whether division rounds towards zero or towards negative infinity.

        To operate on negative values, use
        <function>Truncated_Divide</function> and <function>Truncated_Remainder</function>
        or
        <function>Floor_Divide</function> and <function>Floor_Remainder</function>
        to make the rounding behavior explicit.

      </para>

    </section>


    <section xml:id="predicate-operators">
      <title>Predicate operators</title>

      <table>
        <caption>Predicate operators (these all return Boolean)</caption>

        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Operator
            </th>
            <th>
              Types supported
            </th>
            <th>
              Meaning
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x == y
            </td>
            <td>
              All types
            </td>
            <td>
              Is x equal to y?
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x != y
            </td>
            <td>
              All types
            </td>
            <td>
              Is x not equal to y?
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x &lt; y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer, ordered enumerations
            </td>
            <td>
              Is x less than y?
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x &lt;= y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer, ordered enumerations
            </td>
            <td>
              Is x less than or equal to y?
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x &gt;= y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer, ordered enumerations
            </td>
            <td>
              Is x greater than or equal to y?
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x &gt; y
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer, ordered enumerations
            </td>
            <td>
              Is x greater than y?
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr status="unimplemented">
            <td>
              x &lt;= y &lt;= z
            </td>
            <td>
              Integer, ordered enumerations
            </td>
            <td>
              Is y between x and z. Can also use &lt; in either
              position.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x in p
            </td>
            <td>
              Sets, bitmasks
            </td>
            <td>
              Does x match pattern p?
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x not in p
            </td>
            <td>
              Sets, bitmasks
            </td>
            <td>
              Does x not match pattern p?
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="boolean-and-bitvector-operators">
      <title>Boolean and bitvector operators</title>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Operator
            </th>
            <th>
              Types supported
            </th>
            <th>
              Meaning
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x and y
            </td>
            <td>
              Boolean, Bits
            </td>
            <td>
              Evaluate both x and y, return bitwise and
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x and then y
            </td>
            <td>
              Boolean
            </td>
            <td>
              Evaluate x. If False then False. Otherwise evaluate y
              and return y.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x or y
            </td>
            <td>
              Boolean, Bits
            </td>
            <td>
              Evaluate both x and y, return bitwise or
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x or else y
            </td>
            <td>
              Boolean
            </td>
            <td>
              Evaluate x. If True then True. Otherwise evaluate y and
              return y.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              x xor y
            </td>
            <td>
              Bits
            </td>
            <td>
              Evaluate both x and y, return bitwise xor
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              not x
            </td>
            <td>
              Boolean, Bits
            </td>
            <td>
              Boolean or bitwise negation of x.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>
              x ++ y
            </td>
            <td>
              Bits
            </td>
            <td>
              Concatenate two bitvectors with x as most significant bits.
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      The operators <literal>and then</literal> and
      <literal>or else</literal>
      provide <quote>short-circuiting</quote> behavior
      similar to <literal>x &amp;&amp; y</literal>
      and <literal>x || y</literal>
      in C/C++.

    </section>

    <section xml:id="if-expressions">
      <title>If expressions</title>

      <programlisting>
if-expression = 'if' boolean-expression 'then' expression
                { 'elsif' expression 'then' expression }
                'else' expression
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        An if-expression evaluates boolean guard-expressions
        until the first <literal>True</literal> guard is found;
        and then the corresponding value-expression is evaluated and returned.

        If no guard-expression evaluate to <literal>True</literal> the
        final default expression is evaluated and returned.
      </para>

      <para>
        Parentheses are required around
        the entire if statement if any parsing ambiguity could result.

        That is, the final value-expression is not atomic and
        the overall expression is not at the top level.
      </para>

      <para>
        For example,
      </para>

      <programlisting>
x := if c then 1 else 2;
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        does not require parentheses but, parentheses are needed in
        both of these statements
      </para>

      <programlisting>
x := if c then 1 else (2 * y);
x := (if c then 1 else 2) * y;
      </programlisting>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="case-expressions" status="unimplemented">
      <title>Case expressions</title>

      <para>
        todo: decide whether to add these. And, if so, do they end with
        <literal>end</literal> or do they follow similar rules to
        <quote>if</quote> about parentheses?
      </para>

      <blockquote>
        <para>
          x := case size of <quote>00</quote> =&gt; 8, <quote>01</quote>
          =&gt; 16, <quote>10</quote> =&gt; 32, <quote>11</quote> =&gt;
          64;
        </para>
      </blockquote>

      <para>
        Todo: should these require the <literal>when</literal> keyword,
        or use <literal>,</literal> or <literal>;</literal> or
        <literal>|</literal> or <literal>when</literal> as the separator
        between clauses? Todo: check what other languages do.
      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="indexing-expressions">
      <title>Indexing and bitslice expressions</title>

      <programlisting>
slice-expression = identifier '[' slice ']'
slice = expression
      | expression ':'  expression
      | expression '+:' expression
      | expression '-:' expression
      | expression '*:' expression
      </programlisting>

      <unorderedlist>

        <listitem>
          <para>
            If an identifier <variable>B</variable> has type <literal>Bits(n)</literal>,
            then <literal>B[…]</literal> is used to extract a slice from the bitvector.
          </para>

          <orderedlist numeration="arabic" spacing="compact">

            <listitem>
              <para>
                <literal>B[i]</literal>
                (bit index)
                returns the <literal>i</literal>th element
                of the bitvector <literal>B</literal>.
                Requires that <literal>i in {0 .. n-1}</literal>.
              </para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para>
                <literal>B[i : j]</literal>
                (range-based bitslice)
                returns bits <literal>j</literal> up to <literal>i</literal>
                (inclusive)
                of the bitvector <literal>B</literal>.

                Requires that <literal>i in {j-1 .. n-1}</literal>
                and <literal>j in {0 .. i+1}</literal>.
              </para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para>
                <literal>B[i +: j]</literal>
                (width-based bitslice)
                returns bits <literal>i</literal> up to <literal>i+j-1</literal>
                (inclusive)
                of the bitvector <literal>B</literal>.

                Requires that <literal>i in {0 .. n-1}</literal>
                and <literal>j in {0 .. n-i}</literal>.
              </para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para>
                <literal>B[i -: j]</literal>
                (width-based bitslice)
                returns bits <literal>i</literal> down to <literal>i-j+1</literal>
                (inclusive)
                of the bitvector <literal>B</literal>.

                Requires that <literal>i in {0 .. n-1}</literal>
                and <literal>j in {0 .. i}</literal>.
              </para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem>
              <para>
                <literal>B[i *: j]</literal>
                (element bitslice)
                returns bits <literal>i*j</literal> up to <literal>i*j + j-1</literal>
                (inclusive)
                of the bitvector <literal>B</literal>.

                Requires that <literal>i in {0 .. n/j}</literal>
                and <literal>n % j == 0</literal>.
              </para>
            </listitem>

            <listitem status="unimplemented">
              <para>
                <literal>B[i, j +: k]</literal> - any combination of the above -
                the concatenation of a number of individual bitslices
              </para>
            </listitem>

          </orderedlist>
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <para>
            If an identifier has array type, then <literal>'[' expression ']'</literal> is used to extract
            an element from the array.

            (In the future, we may extend array indexing to support slices as well.)
          </para>

          <para>
            The index must be in the range <literal>{0..n-1}</literal> where <literal>n</literal>
            is the length of the array.
          </para>

        </listitem>

      </unorderedlist>

      Note that the same syntax can also be used for function calls.

    </section>

    <section xml:id="aggregate-initializers-and-updates">
      <title>Aggregate initializers and updates</title>

      <programlisting>
aggregate-expression = identifier [ '(' expression-list ')' ] '{' field-assignment-list '}'
                     | '(' expression-list ')'
                     | 'array' '(' expression-list ')'
                     | expression 'with' '{' change-list '}'

field-assignment = identifier '=>' expression

change = identifier '=>' expression
       | '[' slice-list => ']' '=>' expression

slice = expression
      | expression ':'  expression
      | expression '+:' expression
      | expression '-:' expression
      | expression '*:' expression
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        Aggregates consist of records, tuples, and arrays.
        Aggregates can be copied with changes to form new aggregates.
      </para>

      <section xml:id="record-constructors">
        <title>Record constructors</title>

        <para>
          Records are constructed using the name of the record type,
          an optional list of size arguments,
          and a list of field assignments.

          For example, given these record declarations
          <programlisting>
record Int2 = { x : {0..}, y : {0..} };
record FP(e_size : {0..}, size : {e+1..}) = { is_negative : Boolean, exponent : Bits(e_size), fraction : Bits(size - e_size - 1) };
          </programlisting>
          values of type <literal>Int2</literal> and <literal>FP(32, 8)</literal> can be constructed as follows.
        </para>

        <programlisting>
let origin := Int2{ x => 0, y => 0 };
let four := FP(32, 8){ is_negative => False, exponent => 0b1000_0001, fraction => Zero(23) };
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          A value must be associated with every field of the record.

          For readability and consistency, it is recommended that fields
          are written in the same order that they occur in the declaration.
        </para>

        <para>
          Records can be copied with changes to form new records.

          For example,
          <programlisting>
let x1 := origin with { x => 1 };
let minus_four := four with { is_negative => True };
          </programlisting>

        </para>
      </section>

      <section xml:id="tuple-constructors">
        <title>Tuples</title>

        <para>
          A tuple consists of an ordered list of values that may have different types.
        </para>

        <para>
          A tuple is constructed using a list of expressions enclosed in parentheses such as
          <literal>(1, False)</literal>
          or
          <literal>(32, 0xFFFF_FFFF, 7)</literal>.
        </para>

        <para>
          The only way to access individual elements of a tuple is by pattern matching in a
          <link linkend="let-statements">let</link> or <link linkend="case-statements">case statement</link>.
        </para>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="array-constructors">
        <title>Arrays</title>

        <para>
          An array contains an ordered list of values that must have the same type.
        </para>

        <para>
          An array can be constructed by the keyword <literal>array</literal>
          followed by a list of expressions enclosed in parentheses such as
          <literal>array (1, 4, 9)</literal>
          or
          <literal>array (0b00, 0b10, 0b11, 0b01)</literal>.
        </para>

        <para>
          Elements of an array can be accessed using a zero-based integer index.
        </para>

        <para status="unimplemented">
          <literal>array [3] (0 =&gt; Red, 1 =&gt; Green, 2 =&gt; Blue)</literal>
        </para>

        <para status="unimplemented">
          <literal>array [100] (_ =&gt; 0)</literal> (this initializes
              all array entries to zero)
        </para>

        <para>
          Arrays can be copied with changes to form new arrays.

          For example,
          <programlisting>
let a1 := array (1, 4, 9);
let a2 := a1 with {1 => 2, 2 => 3}; // array (1, 2, 3)
          </programlisting>
        </para>

      </section>

      <section status="draft">
        <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
          <listitem>
            <para>
              <literal>(3, 1)</literal> - a record with type
              <quote>(Integer, Integer)</quote>
            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>
              <literal>(x =&gt; 3, y =&gt; 1)</literal> - a record with
              type <literal>(x =&gt; Integer, y =&gt; Integer)</literal>
            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>
              <literal>Point{x =&gt; 3, y =&gt; 1}</literal> - a record
              with type Point.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </itemizedlist>

        <para>
          <emphasis>[Implementation status; records with named fields are
          not implemented yet.]</emphasis>
        </para>

        <para>
          If <quote>B</quote> is a bitvector of length n, then a bitvector
          update can be written
        </para>

        <itemizedlist spacing="compact">

          <listitem>
            <para>
              <quote>B with {i =&gt; x, j:k =&gt; y}</quote>
            </para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>
              <quote>B with {F =&gt; x, G =&gt; y}</quote> - writing to
              fields
            </para>
          </listitem>

        </itemizedlist>

        <para>
          Todo: record constructors and exception constructors use
          function call syntax <quote>E(x,y)</quote> or <quote>E(x =&gt;
          3, y =&gt; 2)</quote>. They can also provide default argument
          values.
        </para>
      </section>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="function-calls">
      <title>Function calls</title>

      <para>
        Function calls invoke a function and either produce a value or throw an exception.

        If the function can throw an exception, both the function definition and the function
        call will be decorated with an exception marker <literal>?</literal> to warn the reader
        that the expression could generate an exception.

      </para>

      <para>
        Functions can be declared using three different syntaxes: using parentheses, using
        square brackets or omitting parentheses/brackets (only allowed if there are no function arguments).

        This flexibility allows the syntax to better reflect the role of the function.

        The function call must use the same syntax that was used in the function definition.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
function-call = function-identifier optional-function-exception-marker '(' actual-argument-list ')'
              | function-identifier optional-function-exception-marker '[' actual-argument-list ']'
              | function-identifier

function-exception-marker = '?'

actual-argument = expression
                | identifier '=>' expression
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        Actual arguments can be matched against non-implicit formal arguments either by position
        (i.e., the i'th actual argument is matched against the i'th formal argument)
        or by name
        (i.e., a named argument <literal>f => a</literal> is used to match the actual
        argument <literal>a</literal> against the formal argument <literal>f</literal>).
      </para>

      <para>
        Actual arguments must be provided for all formal arguments except if the function
        definition provides a default argument.
      </para>

      <para>
        Named expressions can only appear after unnamed expressions.
      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="evaluation-order-of-expressions">
      <title>Evaluation order of expressions</title>

      <para>
        In many languages, the evaluation order of an expression
        can affect the value of that expression or the behavior such as
        modifications of global variables or exceptions thrown.

        To avoid the need for complex reasoning about evaluation order,
        expressions are required to return the same value independent
        of evaluation order.

        This is enforced by the compiler performing a conservative analysis
        of side-effects and exceptions and rejecting expressions that
        could potentially have evaluation-order dependencies.

        An exception to this rule is made for if expressions which evaluate conditions
        in order and then execute the selected sub-expression
        and for
        expressions that use
        <literal>and then</literal> or <literal>or else</literal>
        that evaluate their first argument before optionally executing
        their second argument.
      </para>

    </section>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="patterns">
    <title>Patterns</title>

    <para>
      Patterns are used in expressions (using <literal>e 'in' pattern</literal> and
      <literal>e 'not in' pattern</literal>), in assignments and in conditional statements.
    </para>

    <para>
      There are two types of patterns:

      <itemizedlist>
        <listitem>
          <quote>irrefutable patterns</quote>
          are used to deconstruct aggregate values.
          Matching an irrefutable pattern against a value always succeeds.
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <quote>refutable patterns</quote>
          are used both to deconstruct aggregate values.
          and to test whether the value matches the pattern.
        </listitem>

      </itemizedlist>

    </para>

    <programlisting>
pattern = irrefutable-pattern
        | refutable-pattern
    </programlisting>

    <para>
      Patterns can introduce new immutable variables that are bound to part of the value
      being matched against.
    </para>


    <section xml:id="irrefutable-patterns">
      <title>Irrefutable patterns</title>

      <para>
        Irrefutable patterns are primarily used to bind a value to a number of
        variables or to discard part of a value using a wildcard pattern.

        There are three types of irrefutable pattern.
      </para>

      <itemizedlist>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            Matching a variable identifier pattern against a value introduces a new immutable variable
            with that name and binds the variable to that value.

            Matching always succeeds.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <para>
            Matching a wildcard <literal>_</literal> against a value always succeeds.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <para>
            Matching a tuple of irrefutable patterns against a tuple of values
            is equivalent to matching each of the patterns against each of the values.

            The tuples are required to be of the same length.

            Matching always succeeds.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </itemizedlist>

      <programlisting>
irrefutable-pattern = variable-identifier
                    | '_'
                    | '(' irrefutable-pattern-list ')'
      </programlisting>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="refutable-patterns">
      <title>Refutable patterns</title>

      <para>
        Refutable patterns differ from irrefutable patterns in that
        they may not match.

        This makes them useful in conditional statements.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
refutable-pattern = integer-literal
                  | bitvector-literal
                  | bitmask-literal
                  | '{' set-pattern-list '}'
                  | '(' pattern-list ')'
set-pattern = constant-expression
            | constant-expression '..' constant-expression
            | mask-literal
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        The syntax of refutable patterns and irrefutable patterns overlaps.

        A refutable pattern is a pattern that is not also an irrefutable pattern.
      </para>

      <itemizedlist>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            Matching an integer literal against a value succeeds if the value
            of the literal is the same as the value.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <para>
            Matching a bitvector literal against a value succeeds if the value
            of the literal is the same as the value.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <para>
            Matching a bitmask literal against a value succeeds if all of the defined
            bits of the bitmask literal are the same as the corresponding bits
            of the value.
          </para>
          <para>
            For example, the pattern <literal>0b01xx</literal> matches the values
            <literal>0b0100</literal>,
            <literal>0b0101</literal>,
            <literal>0b0110</literal>, and
            <literal>0b0111</literal>
            but does not match
            <literal>0b0000</literal>, or
            <literal>0b1011</literal>.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <para>
            Matching a list of set-patterns against a value
            succeeds if at least one of the set patterns matches the value.
          </para>

          <para>
            Matching an expression set-pattern against a value succeeds if the value of the expression
            equals the value.
          </para>

          <para>
            Matching a range pattern <literal>lo '..' hi</literal> against a value
            succeeds if the value is inside the inclusive range <literal>lo</literal> up to
            <literal>hi</literal>.

            That is, it matches if <literal>lo &lt;= value and value &lt;= hi</literal>.
          </para>

          <para>
            Matching a bitmask literal against a value succeeds if all of the defined
            bits of the bitmask literal are the same as the corresponding bits
            of the value.
          </para>
        </listitem>

        <listitem>
          <para>
            Matching a tuple of refutable patterns against a tuple of values
            is equivalent to matching each of the patterns against each of the values.

            The tuples are required to be of the same length.

            Matching succeeds only if all patterns match with their corresponding value.
          </para>
        </listitem>

      </itemizedlist>

      <para status="implementation">
        <emphasis>[Implementation note: the exception matching syntax is
        not supported yet: use <quote>when x : E =&gt;</quote> for
        now]</emphasis>
      </para>

      <para status="design">
        Note: if we later choose to support algebraic datatypes, we
        would use the same pattern matching syntax as for exceptions.
      </para>

    </section>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="statements">
    <title>Statements</title>

    <para>
      Statements are used to perform a sequence of actions.

      Statements can fail if they evaluate an expression that fails
      or if they perform an incorrect actions such as writing
      beyond the bounds of an array.

      Statements can read and can modify local state and global state
      and can throw and catch exceptions.
    </para>

    <programlisting>
statement = variable-declaration-statement
          | assignment-statement
          | return-statement
          | assertion-statement
          | if-statement
          | case-statement
          | for-statement
          | while-statement
          | repeat-statement
          | procedure-call
          | throw-statement
          | catch-statement
    </programlisting>

    <section xml:id="variable-declaration-and-initialization">
      <title>Variable declaration and initialization</title>

      <programlisting>
variable-declaration-statement = 'let' variable-declarations [ ':' type ] := expression ';'
                               | 'var' variable-declarations [ ':' type ] := expression ';'
                               | 'var' identifier-list ':' type ';'

variable-declarations = variable-declaration
                      | '(' variable-declaration-list ')'

variable-declaration = identifier
                     | '_'
                     | identifier ':' type
                     | '_' ':' type
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        Local variables can be mutable (can be modified after they are created)
        or immutable (cannot be modified after they are created).
      </para>

      <para>
        The type of a variable can be inferred from the type of its initializer
        so it is not necessary to state the type when declaring a local variable.

        If a type is provided to improve readability, it must match the type
        of the expression.
      </para>

      <para>
        If the type of the expression is a tuple of length n, then the tuple can be
        deconstructed into its component parts using a variable declaration
        of the form <literal>( v1, v2, ... vn )</literal>.
      </para>

      <para>
        For example, if a function <function>F</function> returns a pair of values,
        two variables <variable>x</variable> and <variable>y</variable>
        can be declared as follows
      </para>

      <programlisting>
let (x, y) = F();
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        If the value of an expression or an element of a tuple, is not needed,
        the pseudo-identifier <literal>_</literal> can be used to discard the
        value.

        The most common use of this is when calling a function that returns
        a value for its side-effects and ignoring the return value.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
let _ = Read_Address(address); // check the address is legal but ignore the result
      </programlisting>

      <para status="design">
        todo: are (irrefutable) patterns allowed in assignments.
      </para>


      <para status="design">
        Should 'let' be changed to 'const' to make it clearer that it is
        a constant?

        Functional languages use let for constants; Javascript uses const
        for constants; Rust and Swift use let for constants.
      </para>

      <para status="design">
        todo: should let expressions use <literal>=</literal> instead of
        <literal>:=</literal> to indicate that they are not actually doing an
        assignment.

        This would make the spec a bit quieter but might raise questions in the
        reader about the difference.

        (But maybe they already have that question about let vs. var?)
      </para>

      <section xml:id="variable-initialization">
        <title>All variables must be initialized before use</title>

        <para>
          Mutable variables do not need to be initialized at the point where
          they are declared but they must be initialized before they are read.

          This is enforced by the compiler performing a conservative analysis
          to ensure that every path between declaration and a read contains
          an assignment to the variable.
        </para>

        <para>
          For example,
        </para>

        <programlisting>
var x : Integer;
if … then
    x := 1;
elsif … then
    x := 2;
else
    Std::Unreachable();
endif;
let y := x;
        </programlisting>

        <para>
          Note that, if the else clause was missing, or did not contain
          <quote>Unreachable</quote>, then control flow could reach the
          final line without initializing <quote>x</quote>. This would be
          an error.
        </para>

        <para>
          Note that a structure such as a record or an array must be fully
          initialized. This can be done using either aggregate expressions
          (i.e., record expressions and array expressions) or using a
          previously initialized record or array.
        </para>

      </section>

      <section status="unimplemented">
        <para>
          Patterns can use named fields
        </para>

        <programlisting>
let (x =&gt; tx, y =&gt; ty) := G(3) // G is expected to return a tuple with fields x and y.
        </programlisting>

      </section>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="assignments">
      <title>Assignments</title>

      <para>
        Assignment statements are used to change the value of mutable variables.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
assignment-statement = lhs ':=' expression ';'

lhs = name
    | '_'
    | '(' lhs-list ')'

name = variable-identifier
     | nullary-function-identifier
     | name '[' actual-argument-list ']'
     | name '.' field_name
      </programlisting>

      <table xml:id="table_example_assignments">
        <caption>Example assignments</caption>

        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>
              Syntax
            </th>
            <th>
              Meaning
            </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>

          <tr>
            <td>
              y := y + 1;
            </td>
            <td>
              Increment an Integer variable
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              A[i] := 3;
            </td>
            <td>
              Set element number <literal>i</literal> of an array <variable>A</variable>
              to <literal>3</literal>.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              float.is_negative := True;
            </td>
            <td>
              Set a field <literal>is_negative</literal> of a record <variable>float</variable>
              to <literal>True</literal>.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              RIP := next_rip;
            </td>
            <td>
              Set a variable <variable>RIP</variable> to a new value.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              EAX := Std::Bits::Zero(32);
            </td>
            <td>
              Call an <link linkend="assignment-function">assignment function</link>
              called <function>EAX</function> passing it the argument
              <literal>Std::Bits::Zero(32)</literal>.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              RIP[0] := 0b0;
            </td>
            <td>
              Set the bottom bit of a variable <variable>RIP</variable> to zero.

              Note that this reads the current value of
              <variable>RIP</variable>,
              clears the bottom bit,
              and writes the value back to
              <variable>RIP</variable>.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td>
              EAX[0] := 0b0;
            </td>
            <td>
              Set the bottom bit of a variable <variable>EAX</variable> to zero.

              Note that this calls the nullary function <function>EAX</function>
              to read the current value of EAX,
              clears the bottom bit,
              and calls the assignment function <function>EAX:=</function>
              to write the value back to EAX.
            </td>
          </tr>

        </tbody>

      </table>

      <section status="design">
        <para>
          Structured mutable variables (i.e., records and arrays) can have
          their components assigned to - but note that it must have been
          fully initialized in advance.

          That is, you need to write
          something like <quote>var r = Point{x=&gt;0, y=&gt;0};</quote>
          or <quote>var r = Init_Point();</quote> or <quote>var r : Point;
          … r = Init_Point();</quote> before you can start modifying
          individual fields.

          This is because we are choosing not to try to
          track whether each individual field has been initialized.
        </para>

        <para>
          Note that the lhs syntax is similar to the syntax of irrefutable
          patterns but extended to support component access and restricted
          by omitting field patterns.
        </para>

      </section>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="return-statements">
      <title>Return statements</title>

      <para>
        Return statements terminate execution of the currently executing
        function or procedure.

        If returning from a function, an expression is evaluated to
        produce the return value of the function.

        The return value must match the function return type.

        Return statements are not restricted to only occurring at the
        end of a function. For example,  they can exit in the middle of a loop.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
return-statement = 'return' ';'
                 | 'return' expression ';'
      </programlisting>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="assertions">
      <title>Assertions</title>

      <para>
        Assertions are used to state properties that must hold
        at some point in the execution.

        If the boolean expression evaluates to <literal>False</literal>,
        execution of the entire specification fails.

        It is not possible to catch assertion failures.

        Assertion failure indicates that it is not possible to draw any
        conclusion about the behavior of the hardware being specified.
        The problem should be reported to the authors of the specification
        so that the specification can be corrected.

      </para>

      <programlisting>
assertion-statement = 'assert' boolean-expression ';'
      </programlisting>

    </section>


    <section xml:id="if-statements">
      <title>If statements</title>

      <para>
        If statements conditionally execute a list of statements
        selected by evaluating boolean expressions until the first
        <literal>True</literal> is found.

        If no boolean-expression evaluates to <literal>True</literal>,
        and there is an else-clause, the else clause is executed.

        If no boolean-expression evaluates to <literal>True</literal>,
        and there is no else-clause, the if statement completes
        with no further action.

      </para>

      <programlisting>
if-statement = 'if' boolean-expression 'then' statement-list
               { 'elsif' boolean-expression 'then' statement-list }
               [ 'else' statement-list ]
               'endif' ';'
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        For example,
      </para>

      <programlisting>
if i in {1..31} then
    return R[i];
else
    return Zero(32);
endif;
      </programlisting>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="case-statements">
      <title>Case statements</title>

      <para>
        Case statements conditionally execute a list of statements
        selected by matching a value against patterns
        until the first match is found.

        Patterns can optionally be augmented with a guard expression
        that must evaluate to <literal>True</literal> for the pattern
        to be considered a match.
      </para>

      <para>
        If no pattern matches, an optional default clause is executed.
        If no pattern matches and there is no default clause,
        execution of the statement fails: there is no silent fall-through.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
case-statement = 'case' expression 'of'
                 { 'when' pattern [ guard ] '=>' statement-list }
                 [ 'otherwise' '=>' statement-list ]
                 'endcase' ';'

guard = 'if' boolean-expression
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        The discriminant expression is evaluated exactly once.
      </para>

      <para status="unimplemented">

        Implementations should warn about incomplete pattern matches and
        unreachable clauses but this can is complicated by the use of guard
        conditions.

      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="for-statements">
      <title>For statements</title>

      <para>
        For loops execute a statement list a number of times.

        The loop control variable is incremented each time
        round the loop if the <literal>to</literal> form is used
        or decremented each time round the loop if the
        <literal>downto</literal> form is used.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
for-statement = 'for' identifier ':=' expression ('to'|'downto') expression 'do'
                    statement-list
                'endfor' ';'
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        For example, the following loop executes the loop body 10 times.
      </para>


      <programlisting>
var s := 0;
for i := 1 to 10 do
    s := s + i;
endfor;
assert s == 55;
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        The start and end expressions are evaluated once before execution of the loop body.

        The loop control variable is immutable within the body of the loop
        and only accessible inside the loop.

        The variable can be thought of as if it was declared
        <quote>let i : {e1..e2} := …</quote> at the start of the
        statement list.
      </para>

      <para>
        If e1 &gt; e2, the loop executes 0 times. If e1 == e2, the loop
        executes 1 time. The loop executes <quote>Max(1 + e2 - e1,
        0)</quote> times.
      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="while-statements">
      <title>While statements</title>

      <para>
        While loops execute a statement list as long as the guard condition is <literal>True</literal>.

        The loop body will not be executed if the guard condition is <literal>False</literal>
        when the while statement is executed.

      </para>

      <programlisting>
while-statement = 'while' boolean-expression 'do'
                    statement-list
                  'endwhile' ';'
      </programlisting>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="repeat-statements">
      <title>Repeat statements</title>

      <para>
        Repeat loops execute a statement list until the termination condition is <literal>True</literal>.

        The loop body will always be executed at least once.

      </para>

      <programlisting>
repeat-statement = 'repeat'
                      statement-list
                   'until' boolean-expression ';'
      </programlisting>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="procedure-call">
      <title>Procedure calls</title>

      <para>
        Statements can call functions that do not return a value using a procedure call.

        (To call an assignment function or a function that does return a value use an
        <link linkend="assignment-statement">assignment statement</link>.)

      </para>

      <programlisting>
procedure-call = function-identifier optional-procedure-exception-marker '(' parameter-list ')'

procedure-exception-marker = '?' | '!'
      </programlisting>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="exception-statements">
      <title xml:id="exception-statements_title">Throw and Try-catch statements</title>

      <para>
        Exceptions can be thrown using a throw statement and caught using a try-catch
        statement.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
throw-statement = 'throw' expression ';'

catch-statement =
'try'
    statement-list
'with'
    { 'when' pattern [ guard ] '=>' statement-list }
'endtry' ';'

guard = 'if' boolean-expression
      </programlisting>

      <para status="design">
        There is a very strong argument that
        <quote>throw</quote> should have an exception marker <literal>!</literal>.
      </para>

    </section>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="module-system" status="unimplemented">
    <title>Module system</title>

    <para>
      todo: Use clauses can be used to remove paths and/or rename
      <literal>use A::B</literal> (lets you write <literal>B::C</literal>)
      and
      <literal>use A::B::C as A_B_C</literal>.

      We should be careful of using <literal>use</literal>
      clauses because, if you see a call to a
      function <literal>C(…)</literal>,
      then you will likely search the rest
      of the SDM for a function called <literal>C</literal> and it would be
      hard to find the use clause that would tell you that
      <literal>C</literal> really means <literal>A::B::C</literal>.

    </para>

    <para>
      There are two types of module: atomic modules and compound
      modules. Both types of module define import and export interfaces.
      Both types of module can instantiate modules within them.
    </para>

    <para>
      The difference is that
    </para>

    <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
      <listitem>

        <para>
          An atomic module can contain global definitions. Typically
          these are specified by a list of files containing definitions.
        </para>

      </listitem>
      <listitem>

        <para>
          An atomic module can only instantiate another module once.
        </para>

      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>

    <para>
      while
    </para>

    <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
      <listitem>

        <para>
          A compound module cannot contain global definitions
        </para>

      </listitem>
      <listitem>

        <para>
          A compound module can instantiate the same module multiple
          times and can explicitly specify the imports of each instance.
        </para>

      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>

    <programlisting>
interface I
    function F(x : Integer) -&gt; Integer;
end interface I

interface J
    function G(x : Integer) -&gt; Integer;
    function H(x : Integer) -&gt; Integer:
end interface J

// an atomic module
module Foo
    import A : I;
    export B : I;
definitions
    file &quot;F.isa&quot;; // get some additional definitions from this file
    module C = Bar(A);  // instantiate module Bar - module instance will be called C
    use C::G; // allows us to refer to G instead of having to write &quot;C::G&quot;
    function B::F(x : Integer) -&gt; Integer
    begin
        return A::F(x+1) + G(3) * C::H(x);
    end
end module Foo
    </programlisting>

    <para>
      Note the trick of naming the module the same as the interface so
      that references to the functions will have the same qualifier as
      definitions of the functions.
    </para>

    <programlisting>
// another atomic module
module Bar
    import In : I;
    export C : J; // use of _ means to export while keeping qualifier
    function C::G(x : Integer) …
end

// a compound module
module Compound
    import A : I;  // I is an interface, A is the namespace identifier
    export B : I;
connect
    B = Atomic(A);
end module Compound
    </programlisting>

    <para>
      Todo: In practice, we are more likely to compose modules using
      the module instantiation API so maybe we would never use the compound module syntax?
    </para>

    <para>
      A concrete example where we put all configuration information for
      a specific configuration into a module and use that as an input
      parameter to the IA specification.
    </para>

    <programlisting>
module Config_Atom
    export Config : Processor_Configuration;
    let Config::Have_AVX_512 := False;
    …
end module Config_Atom
</programlisting>

    <para>
      (We would expect to have Config_Xeon too.)
    </para>

    <programlisting>
module IA_Spec
    import Config : Processor_Configuration;
    …
    function …
        if Config::Have_AVX_512 then …
    …
end module IA_Spec

module Atom_Spec
    …
connect
    config = Config_Atom();
    spec = IA_Spec(config);
    …
end module Atom_Spec;
</programlisting>

    <para>
      todo: maybe add a shorthand syntax for adding integer parameters as
      well as interface parameters.
    </para>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="standard-library">
    <title>Standard library</title>

    <para>
      The standard library <literal>Std</literal> provides useful functions
      for use in writing specifications.

      In practice, <literal>use</literal> clauses are used to rename almost
      all of these functions so that, for example, we can write
      <literal>Unsigned(0b111)</literal> instead of <literal>Std::Integer::Unsigned(0b111)</literal>.
    </para>

    <section xml:id="types-2">
      <title>Types</title>

      <para>
        The standard library includes the following types
      </para>

      <programlisting>
type Std::Integer; // built in to the language

type Std::String; // built in to the language

enumeration Std::Boolean (Std::Boolean::False, Std::Boolean::True);

type Std::Bits(n : {0..}) // built in to the language

type Std::Bit = Std::Bits(1);
    </programlisting>

    </section>
    <section xml:id="integer-functions">
      <title>Integer functions</title>

      <programlisting>
// Interpret a bitvector as an unsigned number
function Std::Integer::Unsigned(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; {0 .. 2**size-1};

// Interpret a bitvector as an signed 2's complement number
function Std::Integer::Signed(implicit size : {1..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; {-2**(size-1) .. 2**(size-1)-1};

// Divide left by right and round the result towards zero
// Requires right != 0
function Std::Integer::Truncated_Divide(left : Integer, right : Integer) -&gt; Integer

// Remainder of dividing left by right and rounding the result towards zero
// Truncated_Divide(x, y) * y + Truncated_Remainder(x, y) == x
// Requires right != 0
function Std::Integer::Truncated_Remainder(left : Integer, right : Integer) -&gt; Integer

// Divide left by right and round the result down towards negative infinity
// Requires right != 0
function Std::Integer::Floor_Divide(left : Integer, right : Integer) -&gt; Integer

// Remainder of dividing left by right and rounding the result towards negative infinity
// Floor_Divide(x, y) * y + Floor_Remainder(x, y) == x
// Requires right != 0
function Std::Integer::Floor_Remainder(left : Integer, right : Integer) -&gt; Integer

// Absolute value
function Std::Integer::Abs(x : Integer) -&gt; {0..}

// Minimum of left and right
function Std::Integer::Min(left : Integer, right : Integer) -&gt; Integer

// Maximum of left and right
function Std::Integer::Max(left : Integer, right : Integer) -&gt; Integer

// The smallest value that is an exact multiple of alignment and not less than x
function Std::Integer::Align_Up(x : Integer, alignment : {1..}) -&gt; Integer

// The smallest value that is an exact multiple of alignment and not greater than x
function Std::Integer::Align_Down(x : Integer, alignment : {1..}) -&gt; Integer

// Logarithm of x rounded down
function Std::Integer::Floor_Log2(x : {1..}) -&gt; {0..}

// Logarithm of x rounded up
function Std::Integer::Ceiling_Log2(x : {1..}) -&gt; {0..}

// Test if x is a power of 2
function Std::Integer::Is_Power_Of_Two(x : {1..}) -&gt; Boolean

// Test if x is an odd number
function Std::Integer::Is_Odd(x : Integer) -&gt; Boolean

// Test if x is an even number
function Std::Integer::Is_Even(x : Integer) -&gt; Boolean
      </programlisting>

      <para status="design">
        Should we also add <function>Ceiling_Divide</function> and
        <function>Ceiling_Remainder</function>?
        These might be useful in defining functions like
        <function>Align_Up</function>.

        Should we add the full set of rounding variants including
        rounding away from zero?
      </para>

      <para status="design">
        todo: Should Align_Up/Down functions restrict alignment to power of 2?
      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="bitvector-functions">
      <title>Bitvector functions</title>

      <programlisting>
// Returns a bitvector of length `size` of all zero bits
function Std::Bits::Zero(size : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)

// Returns a bitvector of length `size` of all one bits
function Std::Bits::All_Ones(size : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)

// Test whether a bitvector is zero
function Std::Bits::Is_Zero(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; Boolean

// Test whether a bitvector is all ones
function Std::Bits::Is_All_Ones(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; Boolean

// Create a larger bitvector by concatenating multiple copies of `x`.
function Std::Bits::Repeat(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), copies : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size * copies)

// Extend a bitvector to a larger size, padding the upper bits with zeros
function Std::Bits::Zero_Extend(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), new_size : {size..}) -&gt; Bits(new_size)

// Extend a bitvector to a larger size, padding the upper bits with a copy of the sign bit `x[size-1]`
function Std::Bits::Sign_Extend(implicit size : {1..}, x : Bits(size), new_size : {size..}) -&gt; Bits(new_size)


// Shift a bitvector left by `amount` padding the right hand side with zeros.
// If `amount &gt;= size`, the result is `Zero(size)`.
//
// Note: because the size of the result is the same as the input,
// it is often useful to first Zero/Sign_Extend the input.
function Std::Bits::Shift_Left(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), amount : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)

// Shift a bitvector right by `amount` padding the right hand side with copies of the sign bit `x[size-1]`
// If `amount &gt;= size`, the result is `Repeat(x[size-1], size)`.
//
// Note: because the size of the result is the same as the input,
// it is often useful to first Zero/Sign_Extend the input.
function Std::Bits::Shift_Right_Arithmetic(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), amount : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)

// Shift a bitvector right by `amount` padding the right hand side with zeros.
// If `amount &gt;= size`, the result is `Zero(size)`.
//
// Note: because the size of the result is the same as the input,
// it is often useful to Zero/Sign_Extend the input.
function Std::Bits::Shift_Right_Logical(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), amount : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)

// Rotate a bitvector left by `amount` padding the right hand side with the upper bits of `x`
// If `amount &gt;= size`, the result is the same as `Std::Bits::Rotate_Left(x, amount % size)`
function Std::Bits::Rotate_Left(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), amount : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)

// Rotate a bitvector right by `amount` padding the lower hand side with the lower bits of `x`
// If `amount &gt;= size`, the result is the same as `Std::Bits::Rotate_Right(x, amount % size)`
function Std::Bits::Rotate_Right(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size), amount : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)


// Convert an integer to a bitvector - handling overflow by saturating.
//
// That is, if `x` is outside the range `{0 .. 2**size-1}`,
// the result is either `Zero(size)` or `All_Ones(size)`
function Std::Bits::Unsigned_Saturate(x : Integer, size : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)

// Convert an integer to a bitvector - handling overflow by saturating.
//
// That is, if `x` is outside the range `{-2**(size-1) .. 2**(size-1)-1}`,
// the result is either `Bits(-2**(size-1))` or `Bits(2**(size-1)-1)`
function Std::Bits::Signed_Saturate(x : Integer, size : {0..}) -&gt; Bits(size)

// Return the number of bits set to '0b1' in x
function Std::Bits::Count_Set_Bits(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; {0..size-1}

// Return the number of consecutive zero bits at the top of a bitvector.
// e.g.,. Count_Leading_Zero_Bits(0b0011_0000) == 2
function Std::Bits::Count_Leading_Zero_Bits(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; {0..size-1}

// Return the number of matching bits at the top of a bitvector.
// e.g.,. Count_Leading_Sign_Bits(0b0011_0000) == 2
// e.g.,. Count_Leading_Sign_Bits(0b1110_0000) == 3
function Std::Bits::Count_Leading_Sign_Bits(implicit size : {1..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; {1..size-1}

// Return the number of consecutive zero bits at the bottom of a bitvector.
// e.g.,. Count_Trailing_Zero_Bits(0b0011_0000) == r
function Std::Bits::Count_Trailing_Zero_Bits(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; {0..size-1}

// Test whether there are an even number of bits set in `x`
function Std::Bits::Is_Parity_Even(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; Boolean

// Test whether there are an odd number of bits set in `x`
function Std::Bits::Is_Parity_Odd(implicit size : {0..}, x : Bits(size)) -&gt; Boolean
</programlisting>

      <para status="design">
        Note: the Shift/Rotate functions obey the rule "F(x, c + d) == F(F(x, c), d)"
        for any non-negative integers c and d.
      </para>

      <para>
        Note: it is interesting to note that the functions Is_Zero,
        Is_All_Ones and Is_Parity_Even/Odd are reductions over
        bitvectors using and, or and xor.

        There is no general syntax for defining these.
      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="miscellaneous-functions">
      <title>Miscellaneous functions</title>

      <programlisting>
function Std::Unreachable();
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        <literal>Std::Unreachable</literal> is used to indicate
        that some part of the specification cannot be reached.

        That is, there are no start conditions that would result
        in the function being called.
      </para>

      <para>

        If this function is called, it indicates a bug in the specification
        and it is not possible to draw any
        conclusion about the behavior of the hardware being specified.

        The problem should be reported to the authors of the specification
        so that the specification can be corrected.
      </para>

      <para>

        Calls to this function are primarily used to help readers understand
        the specification but it also helps the compiler
        to detect uninitialized local variables.

      </para>

      <para>
        Note that no exception marker is required when calling this function
        because it terminates execution, does not add any new control flow,
        and does not raise an exception.
      </para>

      <programlisting>
function Std::End_Execution(success : Boolean)
      </programlisting>

      <para>
        <literal>Std::End_Execution</literal> is not normally used in
        a specification but it can be useful when implementing
        helper code that is used when executing a specification.

        The function terminates execution of the specification either
        indicating successful execution (e.g., because some termination
        condition has been met) or indicating unsuccessful execution
        (e.g., after printing an error message).

      </para>

      <para>
        Note that no exception marker is required when calling this function
        because it terminates execution, does not add any new control flow,
        and does not raise an exception.
      </para>

    </section>

    <section xml:id="print-statements">
      <title>Print function</title>

      <para>
        The print function uses a variant of Python f-strings
      </para>

        <programlisting>
Print("x = {x:2d}, y = {y:4x}");
        </programlisting>

      <para>
        which will produce output like <quote>x = 0, y = ff</quote>.
        (Note that we are printing x in a field of 2 characters and y in
        a field of 4 characters).
      </para>

      <para>
        Print statements are not normally used in finished specifications
        but they can be useful when testing/debugging changes,
        in test harnesses, etc.

      </para>

      <para>
        <emphasis>[Implementation note: at the moment, format strings
        can’t use format modifiers like <quote>:2d</quote> or
        <quote>:4x</quote>.]</emphasis>
      </para>

      <para status="design">
        todo: Underneath the hood, this probably depends on operations
        to format values into string buffers. Will we expose that
        implementation detail to users? Would it be useful?
      </para>

    </section>

  </section>
</section>
